ary menu bar to view search functions and return to the homepage. Still, basic tasks, for example scrolling through pages, are simple, fast and free of noticeable slowdown.","fullscreen":true,"importSrc":"http://www.toptenreviews.com/i/rev/scrn/small/50860-kindle-39.jpg","src":"https://dev.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/2qyea2eEmKubyVmCQkCEPE.jpg","credit":"","align":"","id":"2qyea2eEmKubyVmCQkCEPE","mos":"https://dev.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/2qyea2eEmKubyVmCQkCEPE.jpg","alt":""},"id":"8fddb084-ad0d-4e06-9606-cd683691d9bf","type":"image"},{"data":{"paragraphs":["We didn’t have any problems with book formatting in our testing; chapter titles and text breaks were properly set as soon as an eBook finished downloading. In addition, the straightforward reading interface cleanly lays out text and provides options for functions like text search and highlighting.","The Paperwhite has standard hardware and software features found in comparable eBook readers. You can adjust screen brightness levels and access public library collections and subscriptions to major newspapers. As with past Amazon Kindles, you can pay an extra fee during the checkout process to disable sponsored lockscreens.","This Kindle has a notably stellar display that&#39;s virtually identical to the one on the higher-end Kindle models. Its specifications include a 1448 x 1072 display with a pixel density mark of 300 ppi. The screen performed phenomenally during our hands-on testing, rendering sharp blacks and greys. Onscreen text is similarly smooth with virtually no pixelation on individual letters. For comparison, the best eReaders rely on displays that reach the 300 ppi mark. Budget and entry-level eReaders top out at around 167 ppi, which is still perfectly usable."]},"id":"588d631e-a5ea-48f3-8211-d84f7012c5f4","type":"text"},{"data":{"text":"Design &amp; Portability"},"id":"1ecb2059-26ad-4558-8189-584879fe67b4","type":"heading"},{"data":{"path":"/jFmuhs7MnxQY6hb6HxgHS.jpg","link":{"href":"","rel":null,"target":""}